  "text": "TnrA is known to both activate and repress nitrogen-regulated genes during nitrogen-limited growth [CITATION_1] . When nitrogen sources are in excess, the concentrations of intracellular glutamine and other metabolites are thought to become high enough to cause feedback inhibition of glutamine synthetase (GlnA). The feedback-inhibited GlnA captures TnrA to form a protein-protein complex and thereby abolishes the DNAbinding ability of TnrA. By contrast, during nitrogen-limited growth, TnrA is released from the GlnA-TnrA complex and binds to its specific sites on the DNA for the regulation of transcription. Thus, TnrA exerts its regulatory function only in cells grown under nitrogen-limited conditions [CITATION_2] .",
